Food is to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzsins; at its discretion, the lowering of interest rates would favour rising commodity prices and a slight drop in unemployment the emergence of an inflation spiral.
The ECB is aiming to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least barely at the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the middle ground: you have to "agree" inflation to rule out the need for action later.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a 12-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Increased food and energy prices are responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
