Many places are spared on disinfectants
More than a thousand infections have been registered in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overloading of staff - all factors that are not particularly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was already a similar infection here.
The injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly thereafter the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be carried out since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1094 infections triggered by multi-resistent pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the lead physician at the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections, triggered by multi-resistance pathogens, have been safely recorded in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by the MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the means are too high dosed or improperly applied, the well-responsive bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the everyday life of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi said - MRSA simply does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," Tibor Nyulasi said.
Although patients are examined for MRSA when they are delivered to the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is too rare
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the currently prevailing conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for inhibiting the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is predominantly present in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients delivered and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Last but not least, because there are no grants from the state health insurance for this investigation.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from outside the European Union for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but hospitals do not always comply with this directive.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients, or patients in primary care, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Saves on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds are barely in a row, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-placed hospitals it even happens that when disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be much less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government Programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, which is why they are being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment has been recorded in the government programme.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
