Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raises state's risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary" have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Alert Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Zigeuners".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian opposition".
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremes, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since the autumn of 2006, the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been continuously on the rise, so that since the summer of 2007 several organisations called "national self-defense association" have been established.
"These groups are common in defining themselves as a civilian organization, while openly boasting about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (catastrophe protection, national defense, self-defense), citing the inadequacy of the police, the police.
And all this is done in accordance with that method, which attempts to disguise various political aspirations based on the political and party-drivenness of the population as a civic initiative.
