Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of rearranging the working days around the holidays has now established itself, however, the coming year provides us with fewer such days.
Even in the EU and in the Americas, something else is understood by "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days without work.
Unemployment days are usually church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we are also celebrating New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are days without work - the latter is the only way for the New Year celebrations to rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are the 15th of March, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the foundation of the state will be celebrated, on the 1st of May, and on the 1st and 2nd of November, we will commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each on Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “workday shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
If this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finalised, the Minister of Labour has been set by his own regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employers, to public servants and to public service officials.
Excluded are only companies and establishments in which the operation is carried on without interruption, i.e. even on public holidays.
Heuer’s agenda is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formal, as most take the time off for the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve, or the holiday cancelled specifically for this purpose.
Next year, more holidays will fall in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-arrangements on working days than this year.
The calendar will first be "set on the head" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day so that Friday, May 2, can be a rest day.
The second reorganization is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October you will have to finish the Friday, 24 October in advance.
However, the end of the year will definitely be in the sign of the holidays, after December 24, everything is lying and standing, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
