The U.S. Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided together to fight the crisis in the financial markets.
For example, more than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates to which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the U.S. Fed is sending $40 billion for auction, with another 24 making it easy for the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the attacks of September 11 that the central banks of individual states have agreed on a coordinated approach to defending or mitigating the consequences of a financial crisis.
“This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties in the economy, i.e. the growing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend,” wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in a report to his clients.
“The coordinated action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unused loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
"The central banks must have really been afraid of what else can be achieved when they decide to do so," said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, possibly with an impact on global economic growth.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used in lending money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to borrow money from each other, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
“This will have the same effect as further lowering interest rates,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
