Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your vacation, it will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and annoying cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on an island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana was once a warehouse or passage of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the bosses of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the ban) was liked and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were amongst others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise houses grew, cars drove across the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
At the bar of the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails according to your wishes.
And the cult cars of the fifties are driving in Havana to this day because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats in the salty and humid air have long since fallen apart.
Although Havana, especially its oldest part, has come down heavily, nowhere can you find as many wonderful colonial sights around as right here.
Other places are just being cleared out, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings urgently needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, not only in Havana new hotels have been created, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba also offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauges to the sugar factories.
Its fleet has not been renewed for decades, and this is how you can see lush and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have been standing elsewhere in the museum for a long time.
Excursion Destinations
The most important places do not exclude the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So you don’t have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It remains to be mentioned that in Hemingway’s already mentioned estate there is a museum, the visit of which should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense growth.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Her fame and wealth brought her the trade of slaves and sugar.
The richness embodied itself in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it remained unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but for that reason nothing was demolished, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the "valley of sugar factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which is revived after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba, some call it the most beautiful of the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape hardly affected by human interventions.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage List thanks to its pristine nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in fact, it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, there are several mountain tables, of which the most famous is El Yunque.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the pork bay and the island of Isla de Pinos, over the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, over the Santeria, an African religion to which many of the descendants of slaves could confess all this.
But, as they say, it is better to look with your own eyes.
