For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening and subsequently deported.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Muhammad, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be pissed off.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was taken home on Sunday and violated Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this issue begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children suggested eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, according to school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 of the 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Subsequently, the children created a book for the class, with the picture of the bear on it and the picture caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear itself did not wear a shield with this name, but the problem is quite simply that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
