New Concerns About Gas Dispute Between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is raging between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being impaired.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will be charged higher transit fees by Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is taking place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% more for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
"Changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] over Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices drastically up.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but many of them remain underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
