Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind gusts at the Poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected it was flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles.
According to the famous "Ursuppen theory", lightning has caused life on Earth: storms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything more vivid on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, it sometimes dominates temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's devil twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has hit such a completely different development, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, since since the early 1990s no probe was on its way to explore this planet.
The latest research findings, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
“They also show that our neighbouring planet’s commonality with the Earth is greater than initially assumed,” Esa said in a statement.
In addition to the already known vortex wind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the Earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers about Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Space and Physics Cosmica.
The second-smallest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much slower around itself: a Venus day takes 243 Earth days.
Although Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is fixed in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
