Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, in Sweden, manufactured wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol’s factory directory.
Most of the ninety-four glitter boxes listed there from the "Type Stockholm" are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxen of 1968, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now come to a satisfying result: the six "Brillo-Boxes" of Kunhla are also on the Ruhl-Maßen, and the "Wow" of the 1995 "Woodle of the Hupiuss" of the Pont.
The prehistory is shattered, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: these did not come (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but models of them, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to have a few shiny wooden crates produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Time witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which were then entered right into the art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has investigated in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes also three from Swedish private property, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their presspan plates were first ground and smeared, after which white oil paint was added with a pin.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roller without foundation - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve says: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York doesn't come to a different conclusion than the Sampius's 'Modern' version, that's going to conclude.
Already in July, the Authentication Board has announced to comply with the “severe accusations” raised in the case of the soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have been hiding in unrelenting silence.
